WALKS ARE WAVE BYTES
=====================

A bond is one byte. The native format.

  Wave byte: 2 bits per dimension × 4 = 1 byte
  [7:6]=T  [5:4]=D  [3:2]=M  [1:0]=Q
  00=0   01=+1   10=extended   11=-1

  0xC1 = (-1, 0, 0, +1) = port_write
  0x40 = (+1, 0, 0,  0) = read
  0x10 = ( 0,+1, 0,  0) = apply
  0x55 = (+1,+1,+1, +1) = hylo

Extended coordinates: 10 in any 2-bit field means "read next
byte as signed i8 coordinate." Extension bytes follow the wave
byte in T,D,M,Q order, only for dimensions that used 10.
Most bonds are shell-1 (no extensions). Higher magnitudes pay
1 extra byte per extended dimension. This exists because x86
has width-specific opcodes — a lattice-native chip wouldn't
need it.

A walk is a byte array. Format per record:

  byte 0:   wave byte (the bond coordinate)
  [ext]:    signed i8 per extended dimension (T,D,M,Q order)
  byte N:   flags byte
  bytes:    inline args (variable length per flags)

Flags byte: [reserved:2][arg2:2][arg1:2][arg0:2]
  00 = pipeline (no inline bytes, use previous result)
  01 = u8  (1 byte inline)
  10 = u32 (4 bytes inline)
  11 = u64 (8 bytes inline)

  C1 05 E9 6F           port_write(0xE9, 'o')   4 bytes
  C8 FD 28 [u32] [u32]  filld (M=-3 extended)   11 bytes
  80 07 02 [u32]         rdd (T=+7 extended)      7 bytes

Walker control (reserved bytes >= 0xFC, not bonds):
  0xFE + u32 = skip_z:    skip N bytes forward if pipeline == 0
  0xFD + u32 = skip_nz:   skip N bytes forward if pipeline != 0
  0xFC + u32 = loop_back: rewind N bytes if pipeline != 0


