LOOP PIPELINE — HOW WALKS USE LOOPS
========================================

The foundational primitive. Everything above loops depends on this.

Loop empty check (~4 bonds):

  read(loop + WCURSOR)      → pipeline = write_cursor
  write(stash, pipeline)     → save write_cursor (temp)
  read(loop + SCRATCHA)      → pipeline = reader's own cursor
  test(pipeline, stash)      → 1 if equal (empty), 0 if has data

Loop read (~10 bonds):

  read(loop + SCRATCHA)      → pipeline = reader's cursor
  AND(pipeline, mask)        → slot index
  atom TD(pipeline, recsz)   → byte offset (slot × record_size)
  add(buf_addr, pipeline)    → slot address
  read(pipeline)             → the data
  write(stash, pipeline)     → save data (temp)
  read(loop + SCRATCHA)      → reader's cursor
  increment                  → cursor + 1
  write(loop + SCRATCHA)     → advance reader's own cursor
  read(stash)                → restore data to pipeline

Loop write (symmetric): compute write slot from WCURSOR,
write data, advance WCURSOR. Writer never touches SCRATCHA.

Reader's cursor lives in loop scratch_a [48]. Each reader
has its own. Writer's cursor lives in header [0:7]. Buffer
data is read-only from readers. No shared mutable state.
No atomics. No locks. Boson semantics from the hardware up.

Global stash_a/stash_b still exist for BSP's single-core walks
(kbd/mouse). Multi-core walks (drain) use per-loop scratch only.


