  File names use bracket notation: [order][platform][name][description].asm
  ls shows the whole system. No hunting through directories.

Most devices are non-local (BIOS already set them up):
  pixel buffer, keyboard, serial, VGA text, debugcon, disk.

Genes only for: mouse (PS/2 aux), NIC (MMIO), speaker (PIT).


GENOME SEED
============

Shell 0 = wave (0,0,0,0) = identity = vacuum.
Shell 1 = 16 bonds = fundamental forces.
Everything above = excitations that emerge when walked.

Everything is lazy — atoms AND bonds materialize on first use.
get_atom: cache miss → JIT → cache → return. Cache hit → return.
JIT spinlock serializes concurrent first-use across cores.
No pre-seeding. No startup cost for bonds never used.

  lattice_start:
    init code buffer → walk genesis → signal APs → enter market


LAZY EVERYTHING
================

Nothing exists until something walks there.

  get_atom → cache miss → JIT → cache → return
           → cache hit  → return

The lattice is infinite. Walks collapse it to the finite
subset needed. Nothing pre-allocated. Nothing "just in case."


CURRENT STATE vs DESIGN (read this before coding)
====================================================

The design doc describes the TARGET. The code isn't there yet.
Know the gaps before you start writing.

  Walker format:
    Wave byte walker with magnitude extension. All walks use
    wave bytes. 32-byte walker deleted. See WALKS ARE WAVE BYTES.

  Apply bond calling convention:
    The apply bond (+C) does jmp rdi. The walker sets:
      rdi = arg0 (the function pointer — lands in the callee)
      rsi = arg1
      rdx = arg2
      rcx = pipeline (always)
    The callee gets its OWN ADDRESS in rdi (useless). Real args
    start at rsi. Don't write new apply targets that read rdi
    as a meaningful argument.
    walk_sub is asm scaffolding that bridges apply to walker_wave.
    It stays until the equation can handle nested walks natively.

  Pipeline substitution:
    Flags byte 00 = use pipeline. No sentinel values. To pass
    literal 0, use flags 01 (u8) with inline value 0x00.

  Walker control counts:
    skip_z, skip_nz, loop_back all count in BYTES, not records.
    Compute byte offsets from walk layout.

  BSS:
    Bootloader zeros BSS (rep stosq from __bss_start to __bss_end).
    Page tables in separate .pagetables section (not zeroed).
    No need to explicitly zero BSS variables in genesis.

  Multiboot vs MBR:
    bash build headless = multiboot (-kernel). Skips MBR. No VESA.
    FB address at 0x9100 = 0. Genesis skips filld. Serial only.
    bash build = MBR path. VESA sets mode. Blue screen.
    bash build kvm = MBR path, KVM, display none, debugcon to stdout.
    All three modes show debugcon output (GUI mode too, since session 5).

  Testing:
    ALWAYS test GUI mode (bash build/run) alongside headless. Headless
    skips framebuffer rendering. Bugs in FB access only appear in GUI.
    Build incrementally — one change at a time, test each. Don't
    rewrite multiple files at once. The session 5 crash was caused
    by changing kbd.asm + render_char + genesis simultaneously —
    couldn't isolate which change broke it.
    Debugcon (-debugcon stdio) is ALWAYS enabled in all build modes.
    Don't redirect to /dev/null. If you need to suppress it, pipe
    to /dev/null in the shell, not in QEMU args.

  Bind drain:
    DESIGN: bind bond drains loops, cores self-organize
    ACTUAL: drain_walk built (walks/drain.asm). One AP enters drain
    via CAS (ap_drain_taken). Scans loop_kbd, reads records, calls
    kbd_consumer via walk_sub. BSP runs kbd_walk (producer). Per-loop
    scratch [48:63] isolates reader state from producer. JIT spinlock
    serializes concurrent get_atom. Full multicore (all APs drain) needs
    one core per loop (Pauli exclusion on consumers) — works when there
    are multiple loops. Single-loop = single drainer.

  Equation magnitude coverage:
    DESIGN: any 4 coordinates in, x86 function out. Lazy.
    ACTUAL: atoms fully generative (mul/div chain for any even coords).
    Bonds use 16-pattern dispatch (one per force bitmask). Within each
    pattern, magnitude variants select operation type. Session 9 added:
      W |Q|=11: signed less-than / greater-than
      W |Q|=13: negate / absolute value
      P+W +P+W |Q|=3: max(a,b)
      P+W -P-W |Q|=3: subtract (a-b)
    Rendering math (subtract, compare, abs, max, negate) now available
    as bonds. render_char CAN be rewritten as a walk.
    The dispatch table is still a dispatch table, not a compositor.
    But the magnitude space is now covered for the operations walks need.

  Characters:
    DESIGN: wave bytes in 4D space, SDF rendering
    ACTUAL: SDF renderer (render_char) draws phonetic shapes from
    coordinates. No font file. Genesis renders "nomos" on screen.
    Shapes: circle (vowel), diamond (fricative), square (stop).
    render_char is x86 scaffolding — CAN now dissolve into a walk
    since the equation has subtract, abs, compare-lt, max, negate.

  Input pipeline:
    DESIGN: scancode → phonetic coordinate → loop → consumer → render
    ACTUAL: Producer walk built. Translates PS/2 scancodes to phonetic
    coordinates via 128-entry table. Key-up filtering, unmapped-key
    filtering all working. Coordinates echoed to debugcon.
    BLOCKER: render_char crashes when called from kbd walk after PS/2
    processing in KVM+GUI mode. Works from genesis, works from walk
    start, crashes from after-key-processing position. Triple fault.
    Root cause: render_char is x86 scaffolding called via apply bond.
    x86 scaffolding doesn't play by walker state rules. Fix: rewrite
    render_char as a walk (now possible with session 9 equation).
    Current state: coordinates stored in render_pending BSS var but
    NOT rendered. Rendering disabled pending rewrite as walk.

  Loops:
    DESIGN: walks read/write loops, loop-to-loop pipelines
    ACTUAL: loop read/write primitive built (walks/loop.asm).
    Three macros: loop_empty, loop_read, loop_write.
    Genesis self-test: write 'L', read back, echo to debugcon.
    loop_empty had a bug (returns "has data" after ~4400 idle iterations)
    with the old shared read cursor. Session 9 changed to per-reader
    cursors in scratch_a [48]. Bug may be gone — needs re-testing.
    Loop macros read header fields (mask, recsz, bufaddr) via
    indirect dereference flags. Generic for any loop/record size.
    Uses atom TD (+2,+2,0,0) for slot_index × record_size —
    first atom ever executed in a walk.


